10.text: I have a little shadow that goes

11.text: in and out with me, and what can be the use of him

12.text: is more than I can see. He is very, very like me, from

13.text: the heels up to the head; and I see him jump before me,

14.text: when I jump into my bed.

15.text: One morning, very early, before the sun was up, I rose and found the shining dew on every buttercup;

16.text: but my lazy little shadow, like an arrant sleepy-head, had stayed at home behind me and was fast asleep in bed.

19.text: 1) What is the poem about? 2) Find the rhyming word. a) me – b) head –

20.text: 3) Which line says that both the writer and the shadow are alike?

22.text: 5) Where was the shadow when the writer woke up in the morning? a) in the garden b) in bed at home c) in the playground

23.text: 6) Why does the writer call the shadow an arrant sleepy-head?
